to enact this exclusionary legislation. At the crossroads of knowledge and power, lawyers and doctors had long been dominant forces in French society: they ran hospitals and courts, doubled as university professors, held posts in parliament and government, and administered justice and public health for the nation. Their social and political influence was crucial in spreading xenophobic attitudes and rendering them more socially acceptable in France.Fette traces the origins of this professional protectionism to the late nineteenth century, when the democratization of higher education sparked efforts by doctors and lawyers to close ranks against women and the lower classes in addition to foreigners. The legislatively imposed delays on the right to practice law and medicine remained in force until the 1970s, and only in 1997 did French lawyers and doctors formally recognize their complicity in the anti-Semitic policies of the Vichy regime. Fette's book is a powerful contribution to the argument that French public opinion favored exclusionary measures in the last years of the Third Republic and during the Holocaust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDiscrimination in employmentxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aDiscrimination in employmentzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aLawyersxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aLawyerszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysiciansxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aPhysicianszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aProfessionsxSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxFrancexFrance. 0aProfessionsxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146399040uhttps: